04621nam a22005655i 9780822388814DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223888147 a10.1515/97808223888142doi  a(DE-B1597)551885  a(OCoLC)1171956079  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHD6145b.F66 2008 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a306.3/61509441 aFrader, Laura Levine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreadwinners and Citizens :bGender in the Making of the French Social Model /cLaura Levine Frader. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (358 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Gender in the Making of the French Social Model -- tOne. Reconstruction and Regeneration after World War I -- tTwo. Gender Division, the Family, and the Citizen-Worker -- tThree. Managing the Human Factor -- tFour. Organized Labor, Rationalization, and Breadwinners -- tFive. Toward the Social Model: Citizenship, Rights, and Social Provision -- tSix. Economic Rights and the Gender of Breadwinners: The Depression of the 1930s -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLaura Levine Frader's synthesis of labor history and gender history brings to the fore failures in realizing the French social model of equality for all citizens. Challenging previous scholarship, she argues that the male breadwinner ideal was stronger in France in the interwar years than scholars have typically recognized, and that it had negative consequences for women's claims to the full benefits of citizenship. She describes how ideas about masculinity, femininity, family, and work affected post-World War I reconstruction, policies designed to address France's postwar population deficit, and efforts to redefine citizenship in the 1920s and 1930s. She demonstrates that gender divisions and the male breadwinner ideal were reaffirmed through the policies and practices of labor, management, and government. The social model that France implemented in the 1920s and 1930s incorporated fundamental social inequalities.Frader's analysis moves between the everyday lives of ordinary working women and men and the actions of national policymakers, political parties, and political movements, including feminists, pro-natalists, and trade unionists. In the years following World War I, the many women and an increasing number of immigrant men in the labor force competed for employment and pay. Family policy was used not only to encourage reproduction but also to regulate wages and the size of the workforce. Policies to promote married women's and immigrants' departure from the labor force were more common when jobs were scarce, as they were during the Depression. Frader contends that gender and ethnicity exerted a powerful and unacknowledged influence on French social policy during the Depression era and for decades afterward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aSex discrimination against womenzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aSex discrimination in employmentzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aSex role in the work environmentzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388814zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388814.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013